%S A227933 354963229,448024483,467739719,475313609,525523709,771943583,
%T A227933 790277219,881160173,881160191,881160209,901572019,925569683,
%U A227933 1051470419,1085896727,1110999817,1285560163,1331768783,1455016319,1472310383,1519074619,1628600381,1815368519,1914032047,1914032083,1990306673
%N A227933 Smallest of 6 consecutive primes with equal digital sum.
%C A227933 This sequence consists of those p = A227931(k) for which A227931(k+1) = nextprime(p+1). Terms for which a(n+1) = nextprime(a(n)+1) start a run of (at least) 7 consecutive primes with same digit sum. The first of these are (881160173, 881160191, 1914032047, 4044901709, ...) = row 7 of A395623. If additionally a(n+2) = nextprime(a(n+1)+1), as is the case for n = 8, then a(n) starts a run of 8 with that property, and so on. - _M. F. Hasler_, May 07 2026
%H A227933 M. F. Hasler, <a href="/A227933/b227933.txt">Table of n, a(n) for n = 1..50</a> (based on earlier b-file by Shyam Sunder Gupta), May 07 2026.
%e A227933 354963229 is in the sequence because 354963229, 354963283, 354963319, 354963337, 354963373 and 354963391 are consecutive primes and the sum of the digits of each equals 43.
%t A227933 a = {}; m = 1; s = 1; Do[If[(y = Apply[Plus, IntegerDigits[x = Prime[n]]]) == s , m = m + 1; If[m == 6, AppendTo[a, Prime[n - 5]]], m = 1]; s = y, {n, 2, 200000000}];a (* WARNING: misses some terms *)
%o A227933 (PARI) A227933_first(N)=A395623(6, N) /* will be quite slow */
%o A227933 A227933_start = [p | k<-[2..#A=A227931], A[k]==nextprime(1+p=A[k-1])] /* more practical, with precomputed vector A227931, e.g., from the b-file */
%Y A227933 Cf. A071613 (= column 1 of A395623); A066540, A209396, A210629, A227931 (similar for runs of length 2 through 5).
%Y A227933 Row 6 of A395623.
%K A227933 nonn,base,changed
%O A227933 1,1
%A A227933 _Shyam Sunder Gupta_, Oct 06 2013
%E A227933 Missing a(8), a(9), a(24) and a(47) inserted by _M. F. Hasler_, May 07 2026
